{"title_page": "2022 World Athletics Championships", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{World Championships in Athletics\n|Name = World Athletics Championships<br>Oregon 2022\n|Logo = 2021 World Athletics Championships logo.png\n|Size = \n|Optional caption = Original logo of the 2022 World Athletics Championships\n|dates= 15\u201324 July 2022\n|Nations participating =\n|Athletes participating =\n|Officially opened by   = [[President of the United States]] (expected)\n|Events =\n|previous = [[2019 World Athletics Championships|Doha 2019]]\n|next = [[2023 World Athletics Championships|Budapest 2023]]\n}}\n\nThe '''2022 World Athletics Championships''', the eighteenth edition of the [[World Athletics Championships]], are scheduled to be held in 2022 in [[Eugene, Oregon]], [[United States]].<ref name=RunnersWorld2015-04-16/><ref name=Nytimes2015-04-16/><ref name=TheGuardian2015-04-16/> Originally scheduled to be held from August 6\u201315, 2021, after the postponement of the [[2020 Summer Olympics]], World Athletics raised the possibility of changing the date of the 2021 Championships, including the possibility of moving into 2022.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coe suggests world athletics championships could slip to 2022 |url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-health-coronavirus-olympics-coe/coe-suggests-world-athletics-championships-could-slip-to-2022-idUKKBN21B3GH |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=Reuters |date=24 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> On April 8, 2020, the World Athletics Championships announced that the event would take place from July 15\u201324, 2022.<ref>{{cite news |title=\nDates confirmed for World Athletics Championships Oregon 2022|url=https://www.worldathletics.org/competitions/world-athletics-championships/news/dates-world-championships-oregon-2022 |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=worldathletics.org |date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Host selection==\nThe selection of the host city was announced on April 16, 2015 in Beijing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usatf.org/News/United-States-to-host-2021-IAAF-World-Championship.aspx|title=USA Track & Field - United States to host 2021 IAAF World Championships|work=usatf.org|accessdate=September 5, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"EugeneBBC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/athletics/32333837 |title=Eugene, Oregon awarded 2021 Worlds without bidding process |accessdate=April 16, 2015 |work=[[BBC Sport]]}}</ref> Eugene was selected without a traditional bidding process, though Eugene did put in a bid for the 2019 World Championships, losing to Qatar.<ref name=Nytimes2015-04-16/>\n\n''[[Runner's World]]'' magazine reported that Eugene's selection by [[World Athletics]], then known as the International Association of Athletics Federations, was an \"unusual move\".<ref name=RunnersWorld2015-04-16/> They report the Association \"bypassed the usual bidding process,\" and that the choice of Eugene will make the 2021 event \"the first held in the United States.\" The event will be the second held in [[North America]], after [[Edmonton]], [[Canada]] in [[2001 World Championships in Athletics|2001]].\n\n''[[The Guardian]]'' reported that the lack of bidding triggered concern in European cities that had bid to host the event.<ref name=TheGuardian2015-04-16/>\nThey quoted [[Lamine Diack]], IAAF president, who justified the lack of bidding with the claim the selection of Eugene to host the event, \"enables us to take advantage of a unique opportunity to host a financially successful tournament that may never arise again.\u201d  The lack of bidding for the 2021 event was not unprecedented.  The 2007 World Championship was awarded to [[Osaka]], Japan, without bidding.\n\n==Venue==\n[[Image:HaywardFieldPano.jpg|600px|Hayward Field in 2007, prior to 2018 renovation]]\n\nThe championships will be held in the [[Hayward Field]], at the [[University of Oregon]] in [[Eugene, Oregon]], which is currently undergoing re-construction and will have a capacity of 30,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stadiumdb.com/news/2018/04/new_design_the_best_athletics_stadium_worldwide|title=New design: The best athletics stadium worldwide?|publisher=StadiumDB|date=April 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{Reflist|2|refs=\n<ref name=RunnersWorld2015-04-16>\n{{cite news \n| url         = http://www.runnersworld.com/newswire/eugene-to-host-2021-track-world-championships\n| title       = Eugene to Host 2021 Track World Championships: Oregon City will be first U.S. site of global meet\n| work        = [[Runner's World]]\n| author      = David Monti\n| date        = April 16, 2015\n| accessdate  = August 28, 2015\n| url-status     = live \n| quote       = In an unusual move that bypassed the usual bidding process, the International Association of Athletics Federations awarded Eugene, Oregon, the 2021 World Championships in Athletics in a special vote on the second day of their Council Meeting in Beijingl\n}}\n</ref>\n<ref name=Nytimes2015-04-16>\n{{cite news \n| url         = https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/17/sports/eugene-ore-to-host-first-world-track-championships-in-us-in-2021.html?_r=1\n| title       = Without Bidding, Eugene, Ore., Is Abruptly Awarded World Track Championships\n| work        = [[The New York Times]]\n| author      = Christopher Clarey\n| date        = April 16, 2015\n| page        = B12\n| accessdate  = August 29, 2015\n| url-status     = live \n| quote       = There was surprise in multiple time zones on Thursday when Eugene, Ore., became the first city in the United States to secure the world outdoor track and field championships. It will stage them in 2021 without the usual constraint of having had to win a formal bidding process.\n}}\n</ref>\n<!--unused\n<ref name=IAAF2018-05-04>\n{{cite news \n| url         = https://www.iaaf.org/competitions/iaaf-world-championships/news/2019-world-championships-competition-schedule\n| title       = Innovative and fan-centered 2019 IAAF World Championships\n| work        = [[IAAF]]\n| author      = Doha 2019 LOC for the IAAF\n| date        = May 4, 2018\n| location    = Qatar\n| accessdate  = May 4, 2018\n| url-status     = live \n| quote       = The competition schedule for the IAAF World Championships Doha 2019 has been unveiled today with a new format that enables spectators to have an exciting and engaging event experience. Details for the IAAF World Championships\u2019 first-ever midnight marathon have also been announced with a stunning setting that will showcase the event like never before.}}\n</ref>-->\n<ref name=TheGuardian2015-04-16>\n{{cite news \n| url         = https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/apr/16/iaaf-2021-world-athletics-championships-eugene\n| title       =  IAAF under fire for awarding 2021 World Athletics Championships to Eugene \n| work        = [[The Guardian]]\n| date        = April 16, 2015\n| accessdate  = August 29, 2015\n| url-status     = live \n}}\n</ref>\n}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2021 World Para Athletics Championships]]\n\n{{IAAF World Championships in Athletics}}\n{{2021 in athletics}}\n{{Portal bar|Athletics|United States}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Athletics, World Championships, 2021}}\n[[Category:World Athletics Championships|2021]]\n[[Category:2022 in athletics (track and field)|World Championships]]\n[[Category:Scheduled sports events]]\n[[Category:Sports in Eugene, Oregon]]\n[[Category:International track and field competitions hosted by the United States]]\n[[Category:2022 in American sports]]\n[[Category:2022 in sports in Oregon]]\n[[Category:August 2022 sports events in North America]]\n[[Category:Track and field in Oregon]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{World Championships in Athletics\n|Name = World Athletics Championships<br>Oregon 2022\n|Logo = 2021 World Athletics Championships logo.png\n|Size = \n|Optional caption = Original logo of the 2022 World Athletics Championships\n|dates= 15\u201324 July 2022\n|Nations participating =\n|Athletes participating =\n|Officially opened by   = [[President of the United States]] (expected)\n|Events =\n|previous = [[2019 World Athletics Championships|Doha 2019]]\n|next = [[2023 World Athletics Championships|Budapest 2023]]\n}}\n\nThe '''2022 World Athletics Championships''', the eighteenth edition of the [[World Athletics Championships]], are scheduled to be held in 2022 in [[Eugene, Oregon]], [[United States]].<ref name=RunnersWorld2015-04-16/><ref name=Nytimes2015-04-16/><ref name=TheGuardian2015-04-16/> Originally scheduled to be held from August 6\u201315, 2021, after the postponement of the [[2020 Summer Olympics]], World Athletics raised the possibility of changing the date of the 2021 Championships, including the possibility of moving into 2022.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coe suggests world athletics championships could slip to 2022 |url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-health-coronavirus-olympics-coe/coe-suggests-world-athletics-championships-could-slip-to-2022-idUKKBN21B3GH |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=Reuters |date=24 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> On April 8, 2020, the World Athletics Championships announced that the event would take place from July 15\u201324, 2022.<ref>{{cite news |title=\nDates confirmed for World Athletics Championships Oregon 2022|url=https://www.worldathletics.org/competitions/world-athletics-championships/news/dates-world-championships-oregon-2022 |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=worldathletics.org |date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Host selection==\nThe selection of the host city was announced on April 16, 2015 in Beijing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usatf.org/News/United-States-to-host-2021-IAAF-World-Championship.aspx|title=USA Track & Field - United States to host 2021 IAAF World Championships|work=usatf.org|accessdate=September 5, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"EugeneBBC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/athletics/32333837 |title=Eugene, Oregon awarded 2021 Worlds without bidding process |accessdate=April 16, 2015 |work=[[BBC Sport]]}}</ref> Eugene was selected without a traditional bidding process, though Eugene did put in a bid for the 2019 World Championships, losing to Qatar.<ref name=Nytimes2015-04-16/>\n\n''[[Runner's World]]'' magazine reported that Eugene's selection by [[World Athletics]], then known as the International Association of Athletics Federations, was an \"unusual move\".<ref name=RunnersWorld2015-04-16/> They report the Association \"bypassed the usual bidding process,\" and that the choice of Eugene will make the 2021 event \"the first held in the United States.\" The event will be the second held in [[North America]], after [[Edmonton]], [[Canada]] in [[2001 World Championships in Athletics|2001]].\n\n''[[The Guardian]]'' reported that the lack of bidding triggered concern in European cities that had bid to host the event.<ref name=TheGuardian2015-04-16/>\nThey quoted [[Lamine Diack]], IAAF president, who justified the lack of bidding with the claim the selection of Eugene to host the event, \"enables us to take advantage of a unique opportunity to host a financially successful tournament that may never arise again.\u201d  The lack of bidding for the 2021 event was not unprecedented.  The 2007 World Championship was awarded to [[Osaka]], Japan, without bidding.\n\n==Venue==\n[[Image:HaywardFieldPano.jpg|600px|Hayward Field in 2007, prior to 2018 renovation]]\n\nThe championships will be held in the [[Hayward Field]], at the [[University of Oregon]] in [[Eugene, Oregon]], which is currently undergoing re-construction and will have a capacity of 30,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stadiumdb.com/news/2018/04/new_design_the_best_athletics_stadium_worldwide|title=New design: The best athletics stadium worldwide?|publisher=StadiumDB|date=April 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{Reflist|2|refs=\n<ref name=RunnersWorld2015-04-16>\n{{cite news \n| url         = http://www.runnersworld.com/newswire/eugene-to-host-2021-track-world-championships\n| title       = Eugene to Host 2021 Track World Champions